 part of the Aminet CD collection.
@endnode

@node Purpose "Purpose"

 I thought it would be interesting to see how other user's systems were
 configured, so I wrote "ShoCon.serv".  You might ask why not include all
 the information in my .path file for use with "finger" instead?  Well,
 I'm a "real-time" kind of guy. :)
@endnode

@node Requirements "Requirements"

 OS 2.0+
 AmiTCP 4.0+
 Internet connection
 "inetd" active

 If you are running the server also:

   In your path, you should have the following programs:

     Avail
     Info
     ShowConfig
     ...plus any other executables you have defined in the @{"Config" link Config} file.

   You should also have the following environment variables set accordingly:

     REALNAME
     USERNAME
     HOSTNAME (Your "startnet" script should set this automatically)
     EMAILADDR (May not be the same as USERNAME@HOSTNAME for all of us)
     COMPUTER (Mine's set to "Amiga 1200")
     ...plus any other variables you have defined in the @{"Config" link Config} file.

     NOTE:  For those who don't know how, you enter something like

            >setenv REALNAME "John Doe"
@endnode

@node Installation "Installation"

 1) To install the files, just

      copy "@{"ShoCon.serv" link Server}" to AmiTCP:serv/

      copy "@{"ShoCon" link Client}" to AmiTCP:bin/

    and

      copy "@{"ShoCon.config" link Config}" to AmiTCP:db/

 2) Now you should add the following line to AmiTCP:db/inetd.conf

      ShoCon      stream tcp nowait nobody amitcp:serv/ShoCon.serv

 3) and add the following line to AmiTCP:db/services

      ShoCon      999/tcp

 That's it!
@endnode

@node Client "The Client"

 The "ShoCon" program is just a quick CLI utility that calls the host
 address of a user on port 999.  It then prints out the corresponding
 information from the remote hosts "ShoCon.serv" program.  You must specify
 the host address on the command line, for instance

   >ShoCon dialup30.spasm.com

 Remember that the output will be displayed in the current shell's window.

 To test it out for yourself, you can just enter something like

   >ShoCon localhost
@endnode

@node Server "The Server"

 "ShoCon.serv" is a server called automatically anytime port 999 is
 accessed.  When such a port call is received, the server will send the
 output from "ShowConfig", "Avail" and "Info" over the internet to the
 requesting party.  Thus, anyone can see exactly what hardware, memory and
 drives are being used by you.  Of course, this all depends on how you have
 set up the @{"Config" link Config} file.
@endnode

@node Config "The Config File"

 *** NOTE:  The Config file must be less than 1024 bytes in length. ***

 To offer the most flexibility, I've designed the @{"Server" link Server} to obtain its run-
 time information from a separate Config file.  Thus, this lets the user
 define what user and hardware information should be displayed to the remote
 user.

 The default Config file looks like:

   @{"#" link First} ENV: Variables
   @{"-77" link Separator}
   @{"REALNAME|Real Name" link EnvInfo}
   @{"USERNAME|User Name" link EnvInfo}
   @{"HOSTNAME|Host Name" link EnvInfo}
   @{"EMAILADDR|    Email" link EnvInfo}

   @{"COMPUTER| Computer" link EnvInfo}
   @{"#" link Second} Executables
   @{"-77" link Separator}
   @{"*Hardware Configuration" link Descriptor}

   @{"ShowConfig" link Exe}
   @{"-77" link Separator}
   @{"*Memory" link Descriptor}

   @{"Avail" link Exe}
   @{"-77" link Separator}
   @{"*Device Info" link Descriptor}
   @{"Info" link Exe}
   @{"-77" link Separator}
   @{"#" link Third} EOF


 DO NOT add or subtract the "#" remark lines.  This will mess up the Server.

 Blank lines will be printed as blank lines by the Server.

@endnode

@node First "First Remark Line"

 The first line should always start with a "#".  This is the beginning of
 the Environment Variable section.
@endnode

@node Second "Second Remark Line"

 This remark line signifies the beginning of the executables section.
@endnode

@node Third "Last Remark Line"

 This remark line signifies the end of the Config file.
@endnode

@node Separator "Separator Line"

 -77
 ^ ^
 | |--- Number of "-" characters to print.
 |
 |--- The "-" character signifies a separator line.

 This example would print out 77 "-" characters.  Thus

   -5

 would only print out five "-" characters.  This is useful in separating
 different information so the remote user can spot it quicker.
@endnode

@node EnvInfo "Environment Variable Line"

 ENVNAME|Info
    ^   ^  ^
    |   |  |--- Some descriptive phrase describing the Environment
    |   |       Variable.
    |   |
    |   |--- Separation character.
    |
    |--- Name of Environment Variable found in the "ENV:" directory.

 The remote user will see

   Info: ENVNAME

 where ENVNAME is substituted with its real value.
@endnode

@node Descriptor "Descriptor Line"

 *Info
 ^  ^
 |  |--- Descriptive phrase.
 |
 |--- The "*" character signifies that this is a descriptive line.

 This displays a useful description of what follows to the remote user.
 This is especially useful in the Executables section of the Config file.
@endnode

@node Exe "Executable Line"

 File to be executed by the Server.  All information then being passed on to
 the remote user.
@endnode

@node Bugs "Bug List"

 One minor inconvenience is the less than 1024 byte limit placed on the
 @{"Config" link Config} file.
@endnode

@node History "History"

 1.2     MOD - @{b}ShoCon.serv@{ub}

               The executable is smaller now.  Still learning SAS/C's
               capabilities.  The Server now uses a separate Config file.

 1.1     MOD - @{b}ShoCon@{ub}

               I rewrote the code for the Client so it is smaller.  Now uses
               its own port instead of the TCP: device.

 1.1     ADD - @{b}ShoCon.serv@{ub}

               Now prints out your real name and email address via the
               REALNAME/EMAILADDR environment variables.

 1.0     @{b}Initial Release@{ub}
@endnode

